 who had a tonsure in fulfillment of a religious vow or who had influence and power.","Italian: from the female personal name <i>Corona</i>, of the same derivation as 1 above."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Corona was born in 1340, in Baddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas de Corona, was 26 and her mother, Lucy de Leigh, was 22. She married John Leigh in 1366, in Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1408, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1340–1408":"1340–1408","1340–1402":"1340–1402","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1366–1420":"1366–1420","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","1402":"1402","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1408":"1408","abt 1365":"umbes 1365","1318":"1318","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Coton Hall, Nordley, Alv